    <ImplicitInverseRef name="allCurrentViewObjects" id="27658596-f5c8-4654-9f89-9e0ac038d501">
        <memberTypeInverse/>
        <type name="ObjectSet"/>
        <access>readonly</access>
        <text>Use 'allCurrentViewObjects' and 'allViewObjects' to help reduce notification initiated updating in the table.

Conceptually, we store a set of all objects loaded to the table, and a second sub-set of the ones that are
actually visible. (This is performed immediately after the initial table data load)
We register for generic notifications for all of the objects as we load them, but we only update items from
notification if they are currently visible on the screen. (This reduces the real notification preocessing required
to keep the form up to date)
Then, the user changes the current view of what they can see (by scrolling or re-sizing) or we process
a notification that (adds or removes an item in our visible range ) we refresh the visible items from the database.


'allCurrentViewObjects' - is a set of the objects associated with the lines in the table that are actually visible
to the user at any point in time. Probably only 30 odd in the potential 32,000 that it may have loaded into it.
The contents of this need to change dynamicly as the user resizes the table or scrolls the data.
The method 'setCurrentViewObjects' is used to achieve this. Adding or removing an item during notification processing
also needs to call this. (If 'addViewObject' and 'clearViewObject' are used these already take care of this.) 

'allViewObjects' - is the set of all of the objects loaded into the table. (And registered for notifications)

Use 'clearAllViewObjects' prior to loading the table.
Use 'addViewObject' after adding each item to the table to maintain the collections and the notifications for the object.
Use 'setCurrentViewObjects' after loading the table. 

Use 'clearViewObject' to remove an individual item from the table. (This also de-registers the notification for this object)
Use 'updateViewObject' to update and existing item in the table. It will refresh items in the current view, and just ignore others.

During notification processing use 'allViewObjects' to determine if the item is in the table.
If adding and item, call 'addItem' normally then use also 'addViewObject'.
If updating an existing table item, just use 'updateViewObject'.
If the object is being removed from the table, just use 'clearViewObject'.</text>
    </ImplicitInverseRef>
